# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apicoplast
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:apicoplast/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:apicoplast/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:apicoplast/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:apicoplast/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:apicoplast/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:apicoplast/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:apicoplast/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:apicoplast/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:apicoplast/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:apicoplast/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:apicoplast/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:apicoplast/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:apicoplast/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:apicoplast/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:apicoplast/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:apicoplast/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:apicoplast/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:apicoplast/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:apicoplast/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:apicoplast/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:apicoplast/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:apicoplast/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:apicoplast/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:apicoplast/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:apicoplast/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:apicoplast/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:apicoplast/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:apicoplast/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:apicoplast/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:apicoplast/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:apicoplast/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:apicoplast/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:apicoplast/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:apicoplast/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:apicoplast/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:apicoplast/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:apicoplast/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:apicoplast/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:apicoplast/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:apicoplast/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:apicoplast/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:apicoplast/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:apicoplast/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:apicoplast/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:apicoplast/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:apicoplast/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:apicoplast/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:apicoplast/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:apicoplast/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:apicoplast/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:apicoplast/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The **alveolates** are a group of protists, considered a major clade or superphylum within Eukaryota.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] They are currently grouped with the Stramenopiles and Rhizaria among the protists with tubulocristate mitochondria into the SAR supergroup.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The most notable shared characteristic is the presence of cortical (near the surface) alveoli (sacs).
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] These are flattened vesicles (sacs) arranged as a layer just under the membrane and supporting it, typically contributing to a flexible pellicle (thin skin).
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] In armored dinoflagellates they may contain stiff plates.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Alveolates have mitochondria with tubular cristae (invaginations), and cells often have pore-like intrusions through the cell surface.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The group contains free-living and parasitic organisms, predatory flagellates, and photosynthetic organisms.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Almost all sequenced mitochondrial genomes of ciliates and apicomplexa are linear.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The mitochondria almost all carry mtDNA of their own but with greatly reduced genome sizes.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Exceptions are *Cryptosporidium* which are left with only a mitosome, the circular mitochondrial genomes of *Acavomonas* and *Babesia microti*, and *Toxoplasma*'s highly fragmented mitochondrial genome, consisting of 21 sequence blocks which recombine to produce longer segments.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The relationship of apicomplexa, dinoflagellates and ciliates had been suggested during the 1980s, and this was confirmed in the early 1990s by comparisons of ribosomal RNA sequences, most notably by Gajadhar *et al*.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith introduced the formal name Alveolata in 1991, although at the time he considered the grouping to be a paraphyletic assemblage.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Many biologists prefer the use of the colloquial name 'alveolate'.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Alveolata include around six major groups.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The Acavomonidia and Colponemidia were previously grouped together as colponemids, a taxon now split because each has a distinctive organization or ultrastructural identity.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The Acavomonidia are closer to the dinoflagellate/perkinsid group than the Colponemidia are.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] As such, the informal term "colponemids", as it stands currently, covers two non-sister groups within Alveolata: the Acavomonidia and the Colponemidia.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] As of present, five genera of colponemids are recognized.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The Apicomplexa and dinoflagellates may be more closely related to each other than to the ciliates.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Both have plastids, and most share a bundle or cone of microtubules at the top of the cell.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] In apicomplexans this forms part of a complex used to enter host cells, while in some colorless dinoflagellates it forms a peduncle used to ingest prey.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Various other genera are closely related to these two groups, mostly flagellates with a similar apical structure.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] These include free-living members in *Oxyrrhis* and *Colponema*, and parasites in *Perkinsus*, *Parvilucifera*, *Rastrimonas* and the ellobiopsids.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] In 2001, direct amplification of the rRNA gene in marine picoplankton samples revealed the presence of two novel alveolate lineages, called group I and II.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Group I has no cultivated relatives, while group II is related to the dinoflagellate parasite *Amoebophrya*, which was classified until now in the Syndiniales dinoflagellate order.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Some studies suggested the haplosporids, mostly parasites of marine invertebrates, might belong here, but they lack alveoli and are now placed among the Cercozoa.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The ellobiopsids are of uncertain relation within the alveolates.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Silberman et al 2004 establish that the *Thalassomyces* genus of ellobiopsids are alveolates using phylogenetic analysis, however as of 2016 no more certainty exists on their place.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The development of plastids among the alveolates is intriguing.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith proposed the alveolates developed from a chloroplast-containing ancestor, which also gave rise to the Chromista (the chromalveolate hypothesis).
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Other researchers have speculated that the alveolates originally lacked plastids and possibly the dinoflagellates and Apicomplexa acquired them separately.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] However, it now appears that the alveolates, the dinoflagellates, the Colpodellida and the heterokont algae acquired their plastids from a red alga with evidence of a common origin of this organelle in all these four clades.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] A Bayesian estimate places the evolution of the alveolate group at ~850 million years ago.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The Alveolata consist of Myzozoa, ciliates, and colponemids.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] In other words, the term Myzozoa, meaning "to siphon the contents from prey", may be applied informally to the common ancestor of the subset of alveolates that are neither ciliates nor colponemids.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Predation upon algae is an important driver in alveolate evolution, as it can provide sources for endosymbiosis of novel plastids.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The term Myzozoa is therefore a handy concept for tracking the history of the alveolate group.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The ancestors of the alveolate group may have been photosynthetic.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] The ancestral alveolate probably possessed a plastid.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Chromerids, apicomplexans, and peridinin dinoflagellates have retained this organelle.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] In one school of thought the common ancestor of the dinoflagellates, apicomplexans, *Colpodella*, Colpodellida, and *Voromonas* was a myzocytotic predator with two heterodynamic flagella, micropores, trichocysts, rhoptries, micronemes, a polar ring and a coiled open sided conoid.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] While the common ancestor of alveolates may also have possessed some of these characteristics, it has been argued that Myzocytosis was not one of these characteristics, as ciliates ingest prey by a different mechanism.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] An ongoing debate concerns the number of membranes surrounding the plastid across apicomplexans and certain dinoflagellates, and the origin of these membranes.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] This ultrastructural character can be used to group organisms and if the character is in common, it can imply that phyla had a common photosynthetic ancestor.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Ciliates are a model alveolate, having been genetically studied in great depth over the longest period of any alveolate lineage.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] They are unusual among eukaryotes in that reproduction involves a micronucleus and a macronucleus.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Their reproduction is easily studied in the lab, and made them a model eukaryote historically.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Being entirely predatory and lacking any remnant plastid, their development as a phylum illustrates how predation and autotrophy are in dynamic balance and that the balance can swing one way or other at the point of origin of a new phylum from mixotrophic ancestors, causing one ability to be lost.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Few algae have been studied for epigenetics.
[src:apicoplast/alveolate] Those for which epigenetic data are available include some algal alveolates.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:apicoplast/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] An **amoeba** or **ameba** /əˈmiːbə/ (pl.: **amoebas** or **amebas** (less commonly, **amoebae** or **amebae** /əˈmiːbi/)), often called an **amoeboid**, is a type of cell or unicellular organism with the ability to alter its shape, primarily by extending and retracting pseudopods.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebae do not form a single taxonomic group; instead, they are found in every major lineage of eukaryotic organisms.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoeboid cells occur not only among the protozoa, but also in fungi, algae, and animals.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Microbiologists often use the terms "amoeboid" and "amoeba" interchangeably for any organism that exhibits amoeboid movement.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] In older classification systems, most amoebae were placed in the class or subphylum Sarcodina, a grouping of single-celled organisms that possess pseudopods or move by protoplasmic flow.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] However, molecular phylogenetic studies have shown that Sarcodina is not a monophyletic group whose members share common descent.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Consequently, amoeboid organisms are no longer classified together in one group.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The best known amoeboid protists are *Chaos carolinense* and *Amoeba proteus*, both of which have been widely cultivated and studied in classrooms and laboratories.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Other well known species include the so-called "brain-eating amoeba" *Naegleria fowleri*, the intestinal parasite *Entamoeba histolytica*, which causes amoebic dysentery, and the multicellular "social amoeba" or slime mould *Dictyostelium discoideum*.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebae do not have cell walls, which allows for free movement.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebae move and feed by using pseudopods, which are bulges of cytoplasm formed by the coordinated action of actin microfilaments pushing out the plasma membrane that surrounds the cell.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The appearance and internal structure of pseudopods are used to distinguish groups of amoebae from one another.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebozoan species, such as those in the genus *Amoeba*, typically have bulbous (lobose) pseudopods, rounded at the ends and roughly tubular in cross-section.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Cercozoan amoeboids, such as *Euglypha* and *Gromia*, have slender, thread-like (filose) pseudopods.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Foraminifera emit fine, branching pseudopods that merge with one another to form net-like (reticulose) structures.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Some groups, such as the Radiolaria and Heliozoa, have stiff, needle-like, radiating axopodia (actinopoda) supported from within by bundles of microtubules.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Free-living amoebae may be "testate" (enclosed within a hard shell), or "naked" (also known as gymnamoebae, lacking any hard covering).
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The shells of testate amoebae may be composed of various substances, including calcium, silica, chitin, or agglutinations of found materials like small grains of sand and the frustules of diatoms.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] To regulate osmotic pressure, most freshwater amoebae have a contractile vacuole which expels excess water from the cell.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] This organelle is necessary because freshwater has a lower concentration of solutes (such as salt) than the amoeba's own internal fluids (cytosol).
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Because the surrounding water is hypotonic with respect to the contents of the cell, water is transferred across the amoeba's cell membrane by osmosis.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Without a contractile vacuole, the cell would fill with excess water and, eventually, burst.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Marine amoebae do not usually possess a contractile vacuole because the concentration of solutes within the cell are in balance with the tonicity of the surrounding water.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Some amoebae are predatory and live by consuming bacteria and other protists.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Some are detritivores and eat dead organic material.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebae typically ingest their food by phagocytosis, extending pseudopods to encircle and engulf live prey or particles of scavenged material.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoeboid cells do not have a mouth or cytostome, and there is no fixed place on the cell at which phagocytosis normally occurs.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Some amoebae also feed by pinocytosis, imbibing dissolved nutrients through vesicles formed within the cell membrane.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The size of amoeboid cells and species is extremely variable.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The marine amoeboid *Massisteria voersi* is just 2.3 to 3 micrometres in diameter, within the size range of many bacteria.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] At the other extreme, the shells of deep-sea xenophyophores can attain 20 cm in diameter.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Most of the free-living freshwater amoebae commonly found in pond water, ditches, and lakes are microscopic, but some species, such as the so-called "giant amoebae" *Pelomyxa palustris* and *Chaos carolinense*, can be large enough to see with the naked eye.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Recent evidence indicates that several Amoebozoa lineages undergo meiosis.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Orthologs of genes employed in meiosis of sexual eukaryotes have recently been identified in the *Acanthamoeba* genome.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] This finding suggests that the ''Acanthamoeba'' are capable of some form of meiosis and may be able to undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The meiosis-specific recombinase, Dmc1, is required for efficient meiotic homologous recombination, and *Dmc1* is expressed in *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The purified Dmc1 from *E. histolytica* forms presynaptic filaments and catalyses ATP-dependent homologous DNA pairing and DNA strand exchange over at least several thousand base pairs.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The DNA pairing and strand exchange reactions are enhanced by the eukaryotic meiosis-specific recombination accessory factor (heterodimer) Hop2-Mnd1.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] These processes are central to meiotic recombination, suggesting that *E. histolytica* undergoes meiosis.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Studies of *Entamoeba invadens* found that, during the conversion from the tetraploid uninucleate trophozoite to the tetranucleate cyst, homologous recombination is enhanced.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Expression of genes with functions related to the major steps of meiotic recombination also increase during encystations.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] These findings in *E. invadens*, combined with evidence from studies of *E. histolytica* indicate the presence of meiosis in the *Entamoeba*.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Since the Amoebozoa diverged early from the eukaryotic family tree, these results suggest that meiosis was present early in eukaryotic evolution.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Furthermore, these findings are consistent with the proposal of Lahr et al. that the majority of amoeboid lineages are anciently sexual.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebae have been found to harvest and grow the bacteria implicated in plague.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebae can likewise play host to microscopic organisms that are pathogenic to people and help in spreading such microbes.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Bacterial pathogens (for example, *Legionella*) can oppose absorption of food when devoured by amoebae.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The currently generally utilized and best-explored amoebae that host other organisms are Acanthamoeba castellanii and Dictyostelium discoideum.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Microorganisms that can overcome the defenses of one-celled organisms can shelter and multiply inside them, where they are shielded from unfriendly outside conditions by their hosts.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The earliest record of an amoeboid organism was produced in 1755 by August Johann Rösel von Rosenhof, who named his discovery "Der Kleine Proteus" ("the Little Proteus").
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Rösel's illustrations show an unidentifiable freshwater amoeba, similar in appearance to the common species now known as *Amoeba proteus*.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The term "Proteus animalcule" remained in use throughout the 18th and 19th centuries, as an informal name for any large, free-living amoeboid.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] In 1822, the genus *Amiba* (from the Greek ἀμοιβή *amoibe*, meaning "change") was erected by the French naturalist Bory de Saint-Vincent.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Ehrenberg, adopted the genus in his own classification of microscopic creatures, but changed the spelling to *Amoeba*.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] In 1841, Félix Dujardin coined the term "*sarcode*" (from Greek σάρξ *sarx*, "flesh", and εἶδος *eidos*, "form") for the "thick, glutinous, homogeneous substance" which fills protozoan cell bodies.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Although the term originally referred to the protoplasm of any protozoan, it soon came to be used in a restricted sense to designate the gelatinous contents of amoeboid cells.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Thirty years later, the Austrian zoologist Ludwig Karl Schmarda used "sarcode" as the conceptual basis for his division Sarcodea, a phylum-level group made up of "unstable, changeable" organisms with bodies largely composed of "sarcode".
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Later workers, including the influential taxonomist Otto Bütschli, amended this group to create the class Sarcodina, a taxon that remained in wide use throughout most of the 20th century.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] For convenience, all amoebae were grouped as Sarcodina and generally divided into morphological categories, on the basis of the form and structure of their pseudopods.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoebae with pseudopods supported by regular arrays of microtubules (such as the freshwater Heliozoa and marine Radiolaria) were classified as **Actinopoda**, whereas those with unsupported pseudopods were classified as **Rhizopoda**.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The Rhizopods were further subdivided into lobose, filose, plasmodial and reticulose, according to the morphology of their pseudopods.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] In the final decades of the 20th century, a series of molecular phylogenetic analyses confirmed that Sarcodina was not a monophyletic group, and that amoebae evolved from flagellate ancestors.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] In his scheme, the Sarcodina were divided into the more primitive **Eosarcodina** (with the phyla Reticulosa and Mycetozoa) and the more derived **Neosarcodina** (with the phyla Amoebozoa for lobose amoebae and Rhizopoda for filose amoebae).
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Shortly after, phylogenetic analyses disproved this hypothesis, as non-amoeboid zooflagellates and amoeboflagellates were found to be completely intermingled with amoebae.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] With the addition of many flagellates to Rhizopoda and the removal of some amoebae, the name was rejected in favour of a new name Cercozoa.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] As such, both names Rhizopoda and Sarcodina were finally abandoned as formal taxa, but they remained useful as descriptive terms for amoebae.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The phylum Amoebozoa was conserved, as it still primarily included amoeboid organisms, and now included the Mycetozoa.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Today, amoebae are dispersed among many high-level taxonomic groups.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The majority of traditional sarcodines are placed in two eukaryote supergroups: Amoebozoa and Rhizaria.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The rest have been distributed among the excavates, opisthokonts, stramenopiles and minor clades.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Some multicellular organisms have amoeboid cells only in certain phases of life, or use amoeboid movements for specialized functions.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] In the immune system of humans and other animals, amoeboid white blood cells pursue invading organisms, such as bacteria and pathogenic protists, and engulf them by phagocytosis.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Sponges exhibit a totipotent cell type known as archaeocytes, capable of transforming into the feeding cells or choanocytes.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Amoeboid stages also occur in the multicellular fungus-like protists, the so-called slime moulds.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Both the plasmodial slime moulds, currently classified in the class Myxogastria, and the cellular slime moulds of the groups Acrasida and Dictyosteliida, live as amoebae during their feeding stage.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] The amoeboid cells of the former combine to form a giant multinucleate organism, while the cells of the latter live separately until food runs out, at which time the amoebae aggregate to form a multicellular migrating "slug" which functions as a single organism.
[src:apicoplast/amoeba] Other organisms may also present amoeboid cells during certain life-cycle stages, e.g., the gametes of some green algae (Zygnematophyceae) and pennate diatoms, the spores (or dispersal phases) of some Mesomycetozoea, and the sporoplasm stage of Myxozoa and of Ascetosporea.
[src:apicoplast/amoeboflagellate] An **amoeboflagellate** is any eukaryotic organism capable of behaving as an amoeba and as a flagellate at some point during their life cycle.
[src:apicoplast/amoeboflagellate] Amoeboflagellates present pseudopodia and at least one flagellum, often in separate life stages (as in *Naegleria fowleri*, a human pathogen) or in the same stage simultaneously (as in *Cercomonas*).
[src:apicoplast/amoeboflagellate] The amoeboflagellate cell type has been acquired numerous independent times across the evolution of protists (i.e. primarily unicellular eukaryotes that are not plants, fungi or animals).
[src:apicoplast/amoeboflagellate] The amoeboflagellate phenotype is present in numerous protists that have a crucial phylogenetic position near the origin of animals and fungi, within the vast clade known as Opisthokonta.
[src:apicoplast/amoeboflagellate] It has been described in choanoflagellates such as *Salpingoeca*, filastereans such as *Pigoraptor*, and even some early-branching fungi such as *Sanchytrium*, but it is absent in animals.
[src:apicoplast/amoeboflagellate] The two species of Pluriformea have a wide range of cell types, from cellular aggregations to amoeboflagellates.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] An **apicoplast** is a derived non-photosynthetic plastid found in most Apicomplexa, including *Toxoplasma gondii*, and *Plasmodium falciparum* and other *Plasmodium* spp.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] (parasites causing malaria), but not in others such as *Cryptosporidium*.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] It originated from algae through secondary endosymbiosis; there is debate as to whether this was a green or red alga.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast is surrounded by four membranes within the outermost part of the endomembrane system.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast hosts important metabolic pathways like fatty acid synthesis, isoprenoid precursor synthesis and parts of the heme biosynthetic pathway.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Apicoplasts are a relict, nonphotosynthetic plastid found in most protozoan parasites belonging to the phylum Apicomplexa.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Among the most infamous apicomplexan parasites is *Plasmodium falciparum*, a causative agent of severe malaria.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Because apicoplasts are vital to parasite survival, they provide an enticing target for antimalarial drugs.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Specifically, apicoplasts' plant-like properties provide a target for herbicidal drugs.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] And, with the emergence of malarial strains resistant to current treatments it is paramount that novel therapies, like herbicides, are explored and understood.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Furthermore, herbicides may be able to specifically target the parasite's plant-like apicoplast without any noticeable effect on the mammalian host's cells.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Evidence suggests that the apicoplast is a product of secondary endosymbiosis, and that the apicoplast may be homologous to the secondary plastid of the closely related dinoflagellate algae.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] An ancient cyanobacterium was first engulfed by a eukaryotic cell but was not digested.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The bacterium escaped being digested because it formed a symbiotic relationship with the host eukaryotic cell; both the eukaryote and the bacterium mutually benefited from their novel shared existence.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The result of the primary endosymbiosis was a photosynthetic eukaryotic alga.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] A descendant of this eukaryotic alga was then itself engulfed by a heterotrophic eukaryote with which it formed its own symbiotic relationship and was preserved as a plastid.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast evolved in its new role to preserve only those functions and genes necessary to beneficially contribute to the host-organelle relationship.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The ancestral genome of more than 150 kb was reduced through deletions and rearrangements to its present 35 kb size.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] During the reorganization of the plastid the apicoplast lost its ability to photosynthesize.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] These losses of function are hypothesized to have occurred at an early evolutionary stage in order to have allowed sufficient time for the complete degradation of acknowledged photosynthetic relicts and the disappearance of a nucleomorph.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Most Apicomplexa contain a single ovoid shaped apicoplast that is found at the anterior of the invading parasitic cell.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast is situated close to the cell's nucleus and often closely associated with a mitochondrion.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The small plastid, only 0.15–1.5 μm in diameter, is surrounded by four membranes.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The two inner membranes are derived from the algal plastid membranes; the next membrane out is called the periplastid membrane and is derived from the algal plasma membrane; Finally the outermost membrane belongs to the host endomembrane system.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Within the apicoplast's stroma is a 35 kb long circular DNA strand that codes for approximately 30 proteins, tRNAs and some RNAs.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Particles suspected to be bacterial ribosomes are present.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The plastid, at least in the Plasmodium species, also contains "tubular whorls" of membrane that bear a striking resemblance to the thylakoids of their chloroplast relatives.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The import of proteins into the apicoplast through the four membranes occurs through translocation complexes that originate from the algal plastid (for example:) or from a duplication of the endoplasmic-reticulum-associated protein degradation (for example:).
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast is a vital organelle to the parasite's survival.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Tetracycline, an antibiotic also used to combat malaria infections, is thought to function by targeting the apicoplast.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The destruction of the apicoplast does not immediately kill the parasite but instead prevents it from invading new host cells.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] This observation suggests that the apicoplast may be involved in lipid metabolism.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] If unable to synthesize sufficient fatty acids, the parasite is unable to form the parasitophorous vacuole (PV) that is imperative to a successful invasion of host cells.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] This conclusion is supported by the discovery of type II fatty acid synthase (FAS) machinery in the apicoplast.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast is also thought to have a role in isoprenoid synthesis, which are prosthetic groups on many enzymes and also act as precursors to ubiquinones (involved in electron transport) and dolichols (involved in glycoprotein formation).
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast contains the 2-*C*-Methyl-D-erythritol 4-phosphate (MEP)/1-deoxy-D-xylulose-5-phosphate (DOXP) pathway for isoprenoid precursor synthesis and is the sole site for such synthesis in the *Plasmodium* cell.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] The apicoplast has also been implicated with heme synthesis and amino acid synthesis.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] It is also suggested to have a role in cell development.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] These functions, however, are merely postulations and are not yet conclusively supported by experimentation.
[src:apicoplast/apicoplast] Various iron-sulphur cluster biosynthetic enzymes including SufB or Orf470 have been identified in the apicoplast genome.
